 \in T$ (where $T$ is typically some space of functions) Moment conditions \Er[\psi(W;	heta_0,\eta_0) ] = 0 \in \R^{d_	heta} where $\psi$ known See ml-intro and ml-doubledebiased for examples. The estimation procedure will proceed in two steps: Estimate $\hat{\eta}$ from a neural network Estimate $\hat{	heta}$ from the empirical moment condition with $\hat{\eta}$ plugged in: \En[\psi(W;\hat{	heta},\hat{\eta}) ] \approx 0 @chernozhukov2018 provide high level assumptions on $\hat{\eta}$ and the model that ensure $\hat{	heta}$ is $\sqrt{n}$ asymptotically normal. 1 The key needed assumptions are: Linearizeable score \psi(w;	heta,\eta) = \psi^a(w;\eta) 	heta + \psi^b(w;\eta) + o_p(?) (Near) Neyman orthogonality: \lambda_n := \sup_{\eta \in \mathcal{T}_n} 
